		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012 SI"></a><br><code>sle2012s/paper05</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Domain-specific program profiling and its application to attribute grammars and term rewriting</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthewRoberts.html">Matthew Roberts</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scico.2014.02.011">10.1016/j.scico.2014.02.011</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2012/paper02.html"><em>Profile-Based Abstraction and Analysis of Attribute Grammar Evaluation</em></a> (SLE 2012)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The paper introduces and applies a domain-specific profiling language (dsprofile) tailored to expressing profiling concerns at a higher level.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Profiling is fundamentally a performance-oriented activity, and the work focuses on specifying and extracting performance-related measurements.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The approach concerns runtime profiling and interpretation of execution behaviour to produce profiling results from running programs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The language and its execution are realised via a reusable tooling framework/library (built on Kiama), positioning it as an engineering tool for profiling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
